description: From Latin instimulatus, past participle instimulare (“to stimulate”). See in- and stimulate.

verbs.description: instimulate (third-person singular simple present instimulates, present participle instimulating, simple past and past participle instimulated)
instimulate (third-person singular simple present instimulates, present participle instimulating, simple past and past participle instimulated)

entries.meaning: Not to stimulate; to soothe; to quiet.
examples: They, on the contrary , who have acquir'd their Distempers by too poor and low a Manner of living , on vegetable , insipid and instimulating Food only , which is the Case of most of the Poor or Indigent , must be cured by more generous Living
